  "prompt": "Why is oxalic acid soluble in water?",
  "response": "Oxalic acid is soluble in water due to several factors, primarily stemming from its structure and its ability to form strong hydrogen bonds with water molecules:\n\n*   **Polarity:** Oxalic acid (HOOC-COOH) is a relatively small, polar molecule. The presence of two carboxyl (COOH) groups makes the molecule highly polar. The oxygen atoms in the carboxyl groups are highly electronegative, pulling electron density away from the carbon and hydrogen atoms, creating partial negative charges (\u03b4-) on the oxygens and partial positive charges (\u03b4+) on the hydrogens.\n\n*   **Hydrogen Bonding:** The most significant factor contributing to its water solubility is its ability to form extensive hydrogen bonds with water molecules. The oxygen atoms of the carboxyl groups can act as hydrogen bond acceptors, while the hydrogen atoms can act as hydrogen bond donors. Water molecules (H\u2082O) can similarly act as both hydrogen bond donors and acceptors. This mutual attraction leads to strong interactions between oxalic acid and water, effectively surrounding and solvating the oxalic acid molecules.\n\n*   **Small Size:** The relatively small size of the oxalic acid molecule also plays a role. Smaller molecules are generally easier to solvate, as water molecules can more readily surround and interact with them.\n\nIn summary, the combination of high polarity, the ability to form strong hydrogen bonds with water, and its relatively small size are the main reasons why oxalic acid is soluble in water. These factors overcome the lattice energy that holds oxalic acid molecules together in the solid state, allowing them to disperse and dissolve in water.",
